This template is used to display information on a [[star system]] consisting of 2 stars.  The template should be used as shown below.  Unused arguments may be omitted.  Arguments containing <tt>_a</tt> give information for the first component.  There are corresponding arguments with <tt>_b</tt> which give information for the second component.  For example, <tt>radius_b</tt> gives the radius of the second component.

There are four possibilities for displaying the right ascension and declination.
# Coordinates of the center of mass of the system are displayed, and formatting is done by the template.  Use <tt>ra_system_h</tt>, <tt>ra_system_m</tt>, <tt>ra_system_s</tt>, <tt>dec_system_d</tt>, <tt>dec_system_m</tt>, and <tt>dec_system_s</tt>.
# Coordinates of the center of mass of the system are displayed, and formatting is done by the editor.  Use <tt>ra_system</tt> and <tt>dec_system</tt>.  Use of the {{tl|RA}} template is recommended for formatting the right ascension, and the {{tl|DEC}} template for formatting the declination.
# Coordinates of each component are displayed, and formatting is done by the template.  Use <tt>ra_a_h</tt>, <tt>ra_a_m</tt>, <tt>ra_a_s</tt>, <tt>ra_b_h</tt>, <tt>ra_b_m</tt>, <tt>ra_b_s</tt>, <tt>dec_a_d</tt>, <tt>dec_a_m</tt>, <tt>dec_a_s</tt>, <tt>dec_b_d</tt>, <tt>dec_b_m</tt>, and <tt>dec_b_s</tt>.
# Coordinates of each component are displayed, and formatting is done by the editor.  Use <tt>ra_a_1</tt> and <tt>ra_b_1</tt> for the first line of right ascension and <tt>dec_a_1</tt> and <tt>dec_b_1</tt> for the first line of declination.  If a second line is desired (this may narrow the infobox), use <tt>ra_a_2</tt> and <tt>ra_b_2</tt> for the second line of right ascension, and <tt>dec_a_2</tt> and <tt>dec_b_2</tt> for the second line of declination. Use of the {{tl|RA}} template is recommended for formatting the right ascension, and the {{tl|DEC}} template for formatting the declination. 

If the argument <tt>parallax</tt> is provided and <tt>dist_ly</tt> and <tt>dist_pc</tt> are omitted, the distances will be calculated automatically from the parallax (and the parallax error <tt>p_error</tt>, if provided.)

